WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.929
&gt;&gt; So, I just wanted to thank everyone for
coming.

00:00:02.929 --> 00:00:06.879
And also, I'd like to welcome Kate Roberts
to Google.

00:00:06.879 --> 00:00:12.450
Kate is the Founder and Director of YouthAIDS
and Five &amp; Alive, two marketing programs implemented

00:00:12.450 --> 00:00:17.460
by the Population Services International (PSI),
where she is a Vice President of Corporate

00:00:17.460 --> 00:00:22.890
Marketing and Communications.
Founded in 2001, YouthAIDS is a global education

00:00:22.890 --> 00:00:28.870
and prevention initiative that uses media,
pop culture, music, theatre and sport to stop

00:00:28.870 --> 00:00:34.559
the spread of HIV/AIDS and reach 600 million
young people in more than 60 countries with

00:00:34.559 --> 00:00:40.109
life-saving messages, products, services and
care.

00:00:40.109 --> 00:00:45.589
In 2002 YouthAIDS partnered with MTV to produce
the "Staying Alive" concert, a $3 million

00:00:45.589 --> 00:00:52.680
production broadcast worldwide and featured
on all major news channels, including CNN.

00:00:52.680 --> 00:00:57.449
Other noted productions include an innovative,
celebrity-driven, cause-related marketing

00:00:57.449 --> 00:01:03.249
campaign -- Hear No Evil, See No Evil, Speak
No Evil -- through a partnership with ALDO

00:01:03.249 --> 00:01:09.230
Shoes and four award-winning documentaries
aired on VH1, The Discovery Channel and National

00:01:09.230 --> 00:01:15.970
Geographic aimed at raising awareness about
the global HIV/AIDS crisis as they follow

00:01:15.970 --> 00:01:21.280
YouthAIDS Global Ambassador Ashley Judd through
the most affected areas of Africa, Central

00:01:21.280 --> 00:01:25.290
America and India.
Roberts has been featured in the Washington

00:01:25.290 --> 00:01:31.390
Post, named “Power Player of the Week”
by Fox News, and celebrated on “CNN Heroes.”

00:01:31.390 --> 00:01:36.130
Kate has also been given the honor of speaking
at the Aspen Ideas Festival and has recently

00:01:36.130 --> 00:01:42.410
been awarded “Young Global Leader of the
World 2007” by The World Economic Forum.

00:01:42.410 --> 00:01:47.040
Most recently, Roberts has launched Five &amp; Alive,
an exciting new marketing initiative aimed

00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:52.690
at raising funds and awareness for PSI’s
child survival programs, and has co-founded

00:01:52.690 --> 00:01:57.250
the Global India Fund.
Originally from England, Kate holds a degree

00:01:57.250 --> 00:02:02.450
in Hotel and Catering Management from Southport
University of Art and Technology.

00:02:02.450 --> 00:02:07.510
And lastly, we'll be filming this for YouTube.
So during the Q and A, please make sure to

00:02:07.510 --> 00:02:11.819
use one of the microphones.
Thanks so much, Kate, for coming.

00:02:11.819 --> 00:02:16.180
Kate Roberts: Thank you.
I realize I'm competing with Octoberfest,

00:02:16.180 --> 00:02:23.689
so I really appreciate you guys being here.
So yeah. I'm Kate Roberts, and I founded YouthAIDS

00:02:23.689 --> 00:02:29.120
about ten years ago.
And what I've decided to do today is try to

00:02:29.120 --> 00:02:34.170
tell you the story of building this brand.
I don't know if you are marketeers and that's

00:02:34.170 --> 00:02:43.459
what you want to hear, but I figured by telling
my story, it might really highlight in a different

00:02:43.459 --> 00:02:51.230
way how we actually do development differently.
In fact, I was telling Laura over lunch that

00:02:51.230 --> 00:02:59.060
I'm reading a book right now called "Fred.”
And it's all about a guy who's a postman.

00:02:59.060 --> 00:03:05.489
And it's all about his passion that he's turned
his life around even though he's a postman.

00:03:05.489 --> 00:03:12.079
But he found a passion in his life that made
an ordinary life very, very exciting.

00:03:12.079 --> 00:03:16.950
And I think that I can say that about myself.
I have a very, very ordinary life -- or at

00:03:16.950 --> 00:03:21.909
least had a very ordinary life -- and now
my life is very, very interesting and exciting.

00:03:21.909 --> 00:03:28.739
So I'm here to tell that story.
I am technically challenged, so I really apologize

00:03:28.739 --> 00:03:37.659
for anything that goes wrong with this presentation.
Well, first of all, my journey to do this

00:03:37.659 --> 00:03:44.219
work started with a bet.
And I'm going to get into why that was, but

00:03:44.219 --> 00:03:48.719
first of all to give you a little bit of background
on what I used to do.

00:03:48.719 --> 00:03:55.529
I was in advertising for many, many years
working for Saatchi &amp; Saatchi, an advertising

00:03:55.529 --> 00:03:59.740
agency in Eastern Europe.
I lived pretty much all over the world.

00:03:59.740 --> 00:04:03.230
I grew up on a ship.
My father's a sea captain.

00:04:03.230 --> 00:04:08.180
So I spent my early years traveling around
the world exploring different cultures and

00:04:08.180 --> 00:04:15.980
religions and seeing a lot of poverty along
the way, but decided to go into for-profit

00:04:15.980 --> 00:04:20.060
work working in advertising, which took me
to Eastern Europe.

00:04:20.060 --> 00:04:25.560
I went to live in Russia.
I headed up the Eastern European operations,

00:04:25.560 --> 00:04:37.090
and had a number of big adventures.
Had a run-in with the Russian Mafia, and both

00:04:37.090 --> 00:04:46.949
being kidnapped several times and having adventures
in Russia led me to have to escape the country.

00:04:46.949 --> 00:04:59.150
So I fled from Russia about 13 years ago,
and found my way to Romania to again work

00:04:59.150 --> 00:05:06.050
for Saatchi &amp; Saatchi.
And my focus was cigarettes and alcohol and

00:05:06.050 --> 00:05:10.430
bubble gum, and all things that kids really
liked.

00:05:10.430 --> 00:05:15.259
And it was my job to come up with strategies
of how to get them to smoke more cigarettes

00:05:15.259 --> 00:05:20.930
and eat more bubble gum and drink more soda
pop and whiskey and all the things that were

00:05:20.930 --> 00:05:24.620
destroying their health.
And I have to tell you that I didn't really

00:05:24.620 --> 00:05:29.159
have a problem with that.
And I was kind of good at it.

00:05:29.159 --> 00:05:35.509
And I had the first-class-ticket lifestyle
where I was able to travel all over the world

00:05:35.509 --> 00:05:41.789
and buy nice clothes and buy nice shoes.
And I had a shoe passion -- very expensive

00:05:41.789 --> 00:05:47.199
one.
And I was going along my merry way in Romania.

00:05:47.199 --> 00:05:52.440
Actually, I don't know whether you know much
about Romania, but it's a very small country,

00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:59.300
used to be Communist, and what struck me about
the country was, it was a very passionate

00:05:59.300 --> 00:06:02.720
country, but there was very little resources
for youth.

00:06:02.720 --> 00:06:11.800
There was no real parties or action or color
or fashion.

00:06:11.800 --> 00:06:20.220
And what I decided to do in Romania was to
tap into my world of pop culture and bring

00:06:20.220 --> 00:06:28.350
that to my for-profit clients who were paying
me a lot of money to do their marketing.

00:06:28.350 --> 00:06:39.330
So, along my way of doing these outrageous
promotions, I was approached by a very innovative

00:06:39.330 --> 00:06:47.379
and impressive man, Michael Holscher, who
was representing an organization called PSI,

00:06:47.379 --> 00:06:53.419
Population Services International, for Romania.
And he'd read about me in the media of doing

00:06:53.419 --> 00:06:59.680
these rave parties and cigarette campaigns
and working for Coca-Cola and various different

00:06:59.680 --> 00:07:04.310
brands.
And he simply asked me if I would lend my

00:07:04.310 --> 00:07:12.310
time to helping him develop the first AIDS
campaign in Romania.

00:07:12.310 --> 00:07:18.330
And immediately, I thought to myself, "Hmm.
Well, this might be interesting.

00:07:18.330 --> 00:07:22.190
Maybe this will lead to some award of some
sort.”

00:07:22.190 --> 00:07:28.290
And certainly didn't think at the time how
this could serve the population of Romania

00:07:28.290 --> 00:07:34.419
well.
And we went on -- I agreed -- and the issue

00:07:34.419 --> 00:07:39.990
was that PSI Romania didn't have a lot of
funds to develop the campaign.

00:07:39.990 --> 00:07:47.639
So I looked into what I was doing with my
for-profit clients, and thought, "I could

00:07:47.639 --> 00:07:55.030
go to those different companies to get the
resources necessary to launch this campaign.”

00:07:55.030 --> 00:08:01.759
So we came across an idea called, "In Bed
with You.”

00:08:01.759 --> 00:08:09.530
And we had this big, red, shiny bed that would
travel around to different places to really

00:08:09.530 --> 00:08:15.289
get the issue of HIV out there.
And we would invite various rock stars and

00:08:15.289 --> 00:08:22.090
musicians and actors and actresses to get
into bed with young people to talk about their

00:08:22.090 --> 00:08:28.849
first sexual experience and all the issues
that face young people around reproductive

00:08:28.849 --> 00:08:32.390
health and their first sexual encounters and
safe sex.

00:08:32.390 --> 00:08:38.950
So we developed this campaign, "In Bed with
You," and we were really able to harness the

00:08:38.950 --> 00:08:42.490
resources that were in Romania -- we actually
had the launch party in a brothel.

00:08:42.490 --> 00:08:50.720
And which, of course, was very risky in those
times, but we were able to bring in all the

00:08:50.720 --> 00:08:59.260
big TV stations, all the different media outlets.
And we launched one of the first condoms in

00:08:59.260 --> 00:09:04.959
Romania.
And, within a year, we had managed to increase

00:09:04.959 --> 00:09:10.850
condom use by a hundred percent.
So I got the bug.

00:09:10.850 --> 00:09:16.570
And we were really looking at different innovative
ways of delivering this message and getting

00:09:16.570 --> 00:09:19.870
these condoms into the hands of people who
needed them the most.

00:09:19.870 --> 00:09:25.380
And, of course, it was exhausting.
I became quite obsessed with the campaign

00:09:25.380 --> 00:09:30.240
and decided that I needed to really think
about my direction of what I was doing with

00:09:30.240 --> 00:09:35.339
my life.
So I went off to Africa, and really just to

00:09:35.339 --> 00:09:39.829
rest.
Immediately on landing in South Africa, I

00:09:39.829 --> 00:09:48.370
went to a township to -- really, I was interested
in the country, in the culture, and I noticed

00:09:48.370 --> 00:09:52.950
that on really every corner, there was a funeral
or a graveyard.

00:09:52.950 --> 00:09:59.810
And I just felt something was amiss.
And on asking the local people, they told

00:09:59.810 --> 00:10:04.670
me it was AIDS.
It was HIV, and the stigma that surrounded

00:10:04.670 --> 00:10:09.860
it was so powerful that people weren't even
admitting that their family members had died

00:10:09.860 --> 00:10:13.970
of AIDS.
And at that moment, it struck me, "Well, why

00:10:13.970 --> 00:10:19.220
can't we do here in Africa what we are doing
in Romania?

00:10:19.220 --> 00:10:26.490
In such an innovative way of tapping into
the private sector and using the built-in

00:10:26.490 --> 00:10:32.170
resources and infrastructure in that country
to deliver these much-needed messages about

00:10:32.170 --> 00:10:38.930
stigma and discrimination and condom use in
a much more effective way.

00:10:38.930 --> 00:10:44.449
And not only do that, but to bring these extra
resources to the issue.

00:10:44.449 --> 00:10:49.250
To bring Hollywood, to bring corporations,
to get corporate money, and to really expand

00:10:49.250 --> 00:10:58.910
on what is already happening in that country.”
So back in Romania, I returned very quickly,

00:10:58.910 --> 00:11:06.180
very excited, very, very excited that I had
sort of got this vision of what I wanted to

00:11:06.180 --> 00:11:09.560
do.
And I was actually very excited with the thought

00:11:09.560 --> 00:11:15.339
that I might be able to leave the private
sector and do something worthwhile with my

00:11:15.339 --> 00:11:20.149
life.
So, on arriving back to Romania, we -- a couple

00:11:20.149 --> 00:11:23.260
of things that we did were -- and these are
the "Love Police.”

00:11:23.260 --> 00:11:30.029
The Love Police go down to the Black Sea Coast,
and arrest people on the beach who are not

00:11:30.029 --> 00:11:33.970
carrying condoms.
And with their ticket, they get a condom.

00:11:33.970 --> 00:11:40.220
So we have these Love Police all over Romania,
arresting people.

00:11:40.220 --> 00:11:48.860
Again, a different innovative way of delivering
this message. So, PSI.

00:11:48.860 --> 00:11:55.220
So obviously, I found out then from my friend
and mentor, Michael Holscher, that PSI was

00:11:55.220 --> 00:12:00.949
not just in Romania -- that PSI was all over
the world -- actually in 40 countries.

00:12:00.949 --> 00:12:07.990
And he told me that PSI was a very successful,
global health organization that predominantly

00:12:07.990 --> 00:12:17.120
focused on getting government funding.
And perhaps PSI would be open to hearing about

00:12:17.120 --> 00:12:22.209
this idea of bringing extra resources.
Now PSI all started with this.

00:12:22.209 --> 00:12:26.699
This one condom.
And a couple of trucks.

00:12:26.699 --> 00:12:30.680
And the trucks that you see here were actually
in Bangladesh.

00:12:30.680 --> 00:12:36.949
40 years ago when PSI started, this is how
these condoms were distributed.

00:12:36.949 --> 00:12:40.920
If you think about it, 40 years ago, even
to us, condoms were scarce.

00:12:40.920 --> 00:12:45.639
It was a taboo subject.
So take a country like Bangladesh, where the

00:12:45.639 --> 00:12:50.760
stigma and the cultural situation in the country
was even worse.

00:12:50.760 --> 00:12:56.330
One of our founders felt that this is what
needed to happen, that we needed to bring

00:12:56.330 --> 00:13:02.800
vital health care, health services, health
products to people who really need them the

00:13:02.800 --> 00:13:05.269
most.
So this was all started in Bangladesh from

00:13:05.269 --> 00:13:12.740
the back of a truck.
So PSI's mission, as I said, is really to

00:13:12.740 --> 00:13:17.290
save lives.
I like to joke that "PSI is one of the most

00:13:17.290 --> 00:13:22.850
effective and largest health organizations
in the world that nobody has ever heard of.”

00:13:22.850 --> 00:13:24.519
You hear about CARE.
You hear about Save the Children.

00:13:24.519 --> 00:13:29.589
You hear about UNICEF.
Size relation, we're actually very similar.

00:13:29.589 --> 00:13:36.490
And our focus -- and the focus there in Romania
13 years ago, or 12 years ago, when I was

00:13:36.490 --> 00:13:43.850
there -- was to improve the life, people's
lives and health, all over the world, and

00:13:43.850 --> 00:13:49.220
really to have grassroots, measurable results
in all of the countries.

00:13:49.220 --> 00:13:54.829
So when I joined PSI ten years ago to start
YouthAIDS, we had 40 country programs.

00:13:54.829 --> 00:14:00.839
And now, we're in 65 countries around the
world, reaching almost a billion people with

00:14:00.839 --> 00:14:07.850
these life-saving health products and services.
I would like to say that I can take credit

00:14:07.850 --> 00:14:11.949
for that, but I really can't.
It's a group of extraordinary people, about

00:14:11.949 --> 00:14:20.199
8,000 people worldwide who every day make
it their mission to develop these winning,

00:14:20.199 --> 00:14:27.759
creative solutions to deliver this much-needed
health care services and products to these

00:14:27.759 --> 00:14:30.930
people.
And some of these people you can see here

00:14:30.930 --> 00:14:35.420
in these images.
We go into deepest, darkest Africa, to Asia,

00:14:35.420 --> 00:14:38.470
to all these different places in the world
that are very hard to reach.

00:14:38.470 --> 00:14:45.199
And you must imagine, for instance, that a
sixth of the world does not have access to

00:14:45.199 --> 00:14:48.790
drinking water.
Now, I was privy to the most amazing lunch

00:14:48.790 --> 00:14:54.800
ever today in Google -- which I can not believe
you get every day and every night.

00:14:54.800 --> 00:15:00.570
All those free drinks and free food.
But this is a very different situation around

00:15:00.570 --> 00:15:04.269
the world, obviously.
And we need to find ways to reach people in

00:15:04.269 --> 00:15:14.470
very rural and urban areas with these life-saving
messages and behavior change techniques to

00:15:14.470 --> 00:15:21.110
have them realize why themselves and their
families are getting sick from purely preventible

00:15:21.110 --> 00:15:27.980
diseases.
And some of these diseases are malaria, HIV,

00:15:27.980 --> 00:15:37.269
tuberculosis, pneumonia, reproductive health,
women giving birth to children under trees,

00:15:37.269 --> 00:15:45.310
or having unsafe abortions -- really do account
for hundreds of millions of lives every year.

00:15:45.310 --> 00:15:49.640
So these are some of the countries that we're
in.

00:15:49.640 --> 00:15:55.279
We really do span across the whole world.
We're in 65 countries across five continents.

00:15:55.279 --> 00:16:01.890
Most of these countries I've actually been
to now -- which was actually one of my real

00:16:01.890 --> 00:16:09.670
objectives is to go and learn about the situation
all over the world, about how people are living

00:16:09.670 --> 00:16:16.260
and how they are finding access to this health
care.

00:16:16.260 --> 00:16:23.029
Now, just to explain my internal challenge
a little bit, because when I came to PSI with

00:16:23.029 --> 00:16:31.000
this very fancy idea of reaching out to Hollywood
and the corporate world, PSI was -- and still

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:35.639
is -- a decentralized organization.
So you have to imagine that there's many companies

00:16:35.639 --> 00:16:41.389
all over the world with CEOs heading up those
local programs.

00:16:41.389 --> 00:16:47.120
And they really need a local identity, because
they work locally with the government.

00:16:47.120 --> 00:16:51.649
They have local resources.
They fill a very critical gap between what

00:16:51.649 --> 00:16:55.930
the government is doing and what the private
sector is doing.

00:16:55.930 --> 00:17:03.199
So a highly effective organization already,
but had never told the story of themselves.

00:17:03.199 --> 00:17:08.589
Again, one of the most highly successful health
organizations in the world, but nobody knows.

00:17:08.589 --> 00:17:15.539
So my job was to come in and, first of all,
convince PSI that this is something that I

00:17:15.539 --> 00:17:24.030
should be doing.
And again, PSI had very -- oops, PSI had very

00:17:24.030 --> 00:17:28.339
little brand identity and no equity in the
PSI brand.

00:17:28.339 --> 00:17:33.000
And, quite frankly, the programs themselves
weren't really interested in this YouthAIDS

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:37.169
idea.
So it was very much a case of having to prove

00:17:37.169 --> 00:17:44.780
myself and having to prove this idea of YouthAIDS.
So my mission was to take this idea that I

00:17:44.780 --> 00:17:51.780
had drummed up in the slums of South Africa,
and try to build it into a global brand.

00:17:51.780 --> 00:17:59.320
And I found myself in an office in Washington
really not knowing anybody or really having

00:17:59.320 --> 00:18:03.840
any connections.
So my first job was to reach out to some of

00:18:03.840 --> 00:18:09.160
the champions that I have known over my career
to try to make this work.

00:18:09.160 --> 00:18:15.919
And my first call was to MTV, who I had worked
with in Eastern Europe.

00:18:15.919 --> 00:18:20.450
So I say that, "I am on a mission to find
champions.”

00:18:20.450 --> 00:18:28.210
And my mission was to find these champions,
to gain corporate support, to build vital

00:18:28.210 --> 00:18:35.730
partnerships, to bring the media to put a
public face to what PSI is doing, and to recruit

00:18:35.730 --> 00:18:41.290
celebrity ambassadors, which was a whole journey
all on its own.

00:18:41.290 --> 00:18:46.250
So what I want to do now is -- rather than
me talk -- I always feel that it's much better

00:18:46.250 --> 00:18:47.250
to show videos.

00:18:47.250 --> 00:18:52.150
&gt;&gt; 15 to 24.

00:18:52.150 --> 00:18:59.630
&gt;&gt; I love hip hop.

00:18:59.630 --> 00:19:01.500
&gt;&gt; Beck.

00:19:01.500 --> 00:19:05.240
&gt;&gt; Curty Chestnut.

00:19:05.240 --> 00:19:16.470
&gt;&gt; People have sex.
I have sex.

00:19:16.470 --> 00:19:25.210
You guys have sex.

00:19:25.210 --> 00:19:31.040
&gt;&gt; Justin Timberland.

00:19:31.040 --> 00:19:51.440
&gt;&gt; Get tested to know your HIV status.

00:19:51.440 --> 00:19:54.350
&gt;&gt; [drums]

00:19:54.350 --> 00:20:00.180
&gt;&gt; Alicia Keys.

00:20:00.180 --> 00:20:30.110
&gt;&gt; There's no cure, but there's a way for
you to have.

00:20:30.110 --> 00:20:39.600
&gt;&gt; Wyclef Jean.
This is Wyclef Jean.

00:20:39.600 --> 00:20:49.370
&gt;&gt; YouthAIDS is about kids coming together
for kids. People.

00:20:49.370 --> 00:20:50.380
&gt;&gt; [drums]

00:20:50.380 --> 00:21:05.350
&gt;&gt; YouthAIDS is a global HIV prevention initiative
working in 70 countries to educate young people

00:21:05.350 --> 00:21:10.550
about HIV and AIDS.

00:21:10.550 --> 00:21:11.850
[drums]

00:21:11.850 --> 00:21:38.280
Through partnership with leading global brands
already popular with youth as well as their

00:21:38.280 --> 00:21:53.440
favorite celebrities, YouthAIDS is spreading
the word.

00:21:53.440 --> 00:22:35.430
YouthAIDS partnered with Sanrio and Macy Gray
to promote a T-shirt featuring Hello Kitty.

00:22:35.430 --> 00:23:18.880
Macy Gray: Hey, this is Macy Gray, and I am
angry because AIDS takes the life of one child

00:23:18.880 --> 00:23:19.890
every minute.

00:23:19.890 --> 00:23:24.470
&gt;&gt; One hundred percent of the proceeds benefited
YouthAIDS programs.

00:23:24.470 --> 00:23:28.020
&gt;&gt; Five million further infections every single
year.

00:23:28.020 --> 00:23:35.540
&gt;&gt; Kristin Davis also joined the campaigns
which sold thousands of T-shirts for YouthAIDS.

00:23:35.540 --> 00:23:41.730
&gt;&gt; Missy Elliot partnered with Levi's and
YouthAIDS to create a one-of-a-kind jean jacket

00:23:41.730 --> 00:23:46.190
that was sold on World AIDS Day 2002.

