00:40:51.040 --> 00:40:52.040
own countries.
We also in India worked with Shahrukh Khan,

00:40:52.040 --> 00:40:53.040
Shamit Hassan, and that's really what we do
all over the world by social mobilization

00:40:53.040 --> 00:40:54.040
and tapping into the cultures.
We've made a number of films.

00:40:54.040 --> 00:40:55.040
We've made five documentaries now that have
aired all over the world.

00:40:55.040 --> 00:40:56.040
I would encourage you to look and watch these
films.

00:40:56.040 --> 00:40:57.040
The National Geographic one was following
Ashley and various Bollywood stars around

00:40:57.040 --> 00:40:58.340
India.
I'm not going to do the video thing again.

00:40:58.340 --> 00:41:01.780
I can't stand it.
So you might ask yourself how effective YouthAIDS

00:41:01.780 --> 00:41:05.620
is.
Well, we've raised almost $20 million in cash.

00:41:05.620 --> 00:41:09.910
And probably hundreds of millions of dollars
worth of resources.

00:41:09.910 --> 00:41:14.240
The MTV project alone was $90 million worth
of media.

00:41:14.240 --> 00:41:20.680
And for me, it's all about partnership.
Because we don't want to reinvent the wheel.

00:41:20.680 --> 00:41:25.120
We want to tap into the built-in infrastructure
that exists in the world.

00:41:25.120 --> 00:41:31.100
And we're really looking to form those effective
partnerships. Okay.

00:41:31.100 --> 00:41:35.510
So, in ending, I'm going to show you one last
video.

00:41:35.510 --> 00:41:39.940
Ashley Judd: Good morning.
I am Ashley Judd, and I am the Global Ambassador

00:41:39.940 --> 00:41:41.920
for YouthAIDS.
My first trip as YouthAIDS Global Ambassador

00:41:41.920 --> 00:41:42.920
was designed around the International AIDS
Conference, which at that time was being held

00:41:42.920 --> 00:41:43.920
in Bangkok, Thailand.
Here we are.

00:41:43.920 --> 00:41:56.930
I don't know that much about Cambodia.
I left My Lonely Planet to work at home.

00:41:56.930 --> 00:42:02.660
But in a way I'm glad, because I think it's
really interesting to come to a place like

00:42:02.660 --> 00:42:06.280
this eyes wide open just ready to learn.
I will let them show me what they are about,

00:42:06.280 --> 00:42:08.290
rather than come in with any preconceived
notions whatsoever.

00:42:08.290 --> 00:42:09.410
And so, the journey begins.

00:42:09.410 --> 00:42:12.280
Ashley Judd: We started by visiting a wonderful,
wonderful hospital/hospice, that provides

00:42:12.280 --> 00:42:18.730
end-of-life care for the people who've really
been ravished by opportunistic infections

00:42:18.730 --> 00:42:44.790
and that are really I think very end of their,
you know, losing battles with HIV/AIDS.

00:42:44.790 --> 00:43:09.490
We arrived at a pagoda, which is what they
call their temples, and went inside.

00:43:09.490 --> 00:43:10.490
Then the monks entered.

00:43:10.490 --> 00:43:11.490
[chanting]

00:43:11.490 --> 00:43:33.530
Ashley Judd: It is an enormous pleasure to
sit and have people pray for you.

00:43:33.530 --> 00:43:42.730
It's so totally rocked.
So that was all done and we adjourned outside.

00:43:42.730 --> 00:43:54.920
I met the Watt grannies.
A Watt granny is a Buddhist woman who takes

00:43:54.920 --> 00:43:57.750
on the assignment of caring for at-risk and
vulnerable children.

00:43:57.750 --> 00:44:00.312
It was about the most beautiful collection
of women I've ever seen in my life.

00:44:00.312 --> 00:44:01.312
They were awesome.

00:44:01.312 --> 00:44:02.312
&gt;&gt; Tell them I'll come back and bring my handsome
husband.

00:44:02.312 --> 00:44:03.312
&gt;&gt; [speaking in a foreign language]

00:44:03.312 --> 00:44:04.312
&gt;&gt; [Laughter]

00:44:04.312 --> 00:44:05.312
Ashley Judd: I held some beautiful babies.
Oh man, beautiful babies.

00:44:05.312 --> 00:44:06.312
The hardest things were at night in my hotel
room by myself thinking about the people I

00:44:06.312 --> 00:44:07.312
met and thinking about this beautiful child
named Osweileia, and just knowing that they

00:44:07.312 --> 00:44:08.312
are still in their circumstances.
You know, vulnerable and at-risk is very difficult.

00:44:08.312 --> 00:44:11.660
And I was a part of this afternoon was peer
education.

00:44:11.660 --> 00:44:27.240
So a sex worker who is dynamic and has an
outgoing personality will be asked to help

00:44:27.240 --> 00:44:28.240
educate her peers about HIV, how the virus
is transmitted, and about condoms -- both

00:44:28.240 --> 00:44:44.470
male condoms and female condoms -- and how
to insist that your clients use a condom,

00:44:44.470 --> 00:44:51.780
and how to safely get out of the situation
if the client refuses.

00:44:51.780 --> 00:44:54.590
&gt;&gt; [speaking in a foreign language]

00:44:54.590 --> 00:44:55.590
&gt;&gt; [Clapping]

00:44:55.590 --> 00:45:00.210
Ashley Judd: Thailand was perfect, because
it's the exact opposite.

00:45:00.210 --> 00:45:05.320
We were new in Thailand.
We were just getting started.

00:45:05.320 --> 00:45:19.050
And one of the interesting things that we
were able to do was be involved with the government

00:45:19.050 --> 00:45:20.230
at the very highest level right away.

00:45:20.230 --> 00:45:22.830
Ashley Judd: And the prime minister was gracious
enough during his very busy schedule to give

00:45:22.830 --> 00:45:24.450
us not only an audience but a very ample one.

00:45:24.450 --> 00:45:25.754
Ashley Judd: We went to an orphanage, and
it's very hard core.

00:45:25.754 --> 00:45:26.754
I mean, I've cried more than once over being
in that place.

00:45:26.754 --> 00:45:42.180
It's just not right.
It is not right to have to talk to children

00:45:42.180 --> 00:45:43.400
so young about such adult issues.
But I can't help the fact that they're there.

00:45:43.400 --> 00:45:45.640
And there are a lot of programs and a lot
of government activities directed at preventing

00:45:45.640 --> 00:45:47.080
those children from being on the street in
the first place.

00:45:47.080 --> 00:45:49.180
However, some are already there.
So we have to reach out to the ones who are

00:45:49.180 --> 00:45:53.680
there, identify them, and help them on a consistent
and sustained basis so that they do not become

00:45:53.680 --> 00:45:58.400
HIV positive.
That's what this is about.

00:45:58.400 --> 00:46:07.950
And seeing store front after store front after
store front after store front of these bars

00:46:07.950 --> 00:46:09.840
and karaoke establishments.
I mean, how can I describe what it's like

00:46:09.840 --> 00:46:10.840
to go to a brothel?
Nothing prepares you.

00:46:10.840 --> 00:46:12.380
Absolutely nothing prepares you.
The women in the brothels and the bars and

00:46:12.380 --> 00:46:13.380
the karaoke establishments knew a lot about
HIV/AIDS.

00:46:13.380 --> 00:46:26.690
And I would say that a lot of that was a credit
to PSI YouthAIDS programs.

00:46:26.690 --> 00:46:28.860
The first group of sex workers with whom I
visited were all HIV positive, and they were

00:46:28.860 --> 00:46:32.840
still working in commercial sex.
It's been the journey of a lifetime and a

00:46:32.840 --> 00:46:38.060
trip I've been waiting my entire life to take.

00:46:38.060 --> 00:46:43.080
Ashley Judd: There's absolutely hope, because
PSI YouthAIDS programs work.

00:46:43.080 --> 00:46:49.830
They absolutely 100 percent work.
Being associated with HIV/AIDS associates

00:46:49.830 --> 00:46:53.860
you with compassion, with hope.
And what company doesn't want to be associated

00:46:53.860 --> 00:46:59.030
with that?
And the more creative people are, the more

00:46:59.030 --> 00:47:19.840
broad a population, the messages can reach.

00:47:19.840 --> 00:47:23.800
Kate Roberts: So that really shows the work
that we do on the ground.

00:47:23.800 --> 00:47:27.760
And we've taken our champions and ambassadors
many different times to see these programs

00:47:27.760 --> 00:47:30.030
now.
And it doesn't matter personally how many

00:47:30.030 --> 00:47:33.990
times I go to the field and I see the work
that we're doing.

00:47:33.990 --> 00:47:37.670
I remain so passionate about what we do and
how we do it.

00:47:37.670 --> 00:47:41.910
And the commercial approach that we take.
And you know, I'm on the brand-building side

00:47:41.910 --> 00:47:46.440
of it, but doing journeys like this really
helps me to stay motivated and current and

00:47:46.440 --> 00:47:50.970
creative, which I think is the most important
thing in doing the work that I do.

00:47:50.970 --> 00:47:53.790
So I don't know whether you've got any more
questions?

00:47:53.790 --> 00:47:54.790
[pause]

00:47:54.790 --> 00:47:56.910
Well, thank you very much.
Thank you. Really appreciate it.

00:47:56.910 --> 00:47:57.190
